</li><li class="sense" htag="li" sensenum="2" id="author_sng_2" hclass="sense"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="def" htag="span" hclass="def">the person who creates or starts something, especially a plan or an idea</span></span><ul class="examples" hclass="examples" htag="ul"><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">As the author of the proposal I cannot agree with you.</span></li><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">He is the author of a plan to bring peace to the region.</span></li></ul>      </li><div class="collapse" hclass="collapse" htag="div"><span class="unbox" unbox="wordorigin" id="author2_unbox_5"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">Middle English (in the sense ‘a person who invents or causes something’): from Old French <span class="ei">autor</span>, from Latin <span class="ei">auctor</span>, from <span class="ei">augere</span> ‘increase, originate, promote’. The spelling with <span class="ei">th</span> arose in the 15th cent., and perhaps became established under the influence of <span class="ei">authentic</span>.</span></span></span></div></ol><span class="dictlink-g"><span class="dictlink">See <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/american_english/author_1" title=" definition in American English
